Weather and CitiBike Data Findings

Patrick Lucey

Homepage

Summary of Exploration of the data used for analysis

During the initial phases of analysis, I explored the data to understand the relationships between the variables and if there was any missing or incorrect data. I found that the data was not very clean and required some tidying to be used for analysis. For starters, I had to merge the weather and Citibike data which can be explained more here:Datacleaning . After merging the data, I explored the relationship between the temperature and the number of trips taken by users of the bike-sharing service. I found that the number of trips taken in the summer months was higher than in the other seasons. This led me to want to explore the relationship between temperature and trip duration in extreme weather conditions. I decided to focus on temperatures above 32°C (89.6°F) and to analyze the relationship between temperature and trip duration during the summer months. I also wanted to explore the relationship between time of day and trip duration to see if there were any patterns in trip duration during different times of the day. This led me to create a spline regression model to analyze the relationship between temperature, time of day, and trip duration in extreme weather conditions. The results of the regression model showed that the temperature had a significant impact on trip duration in temperatures above 32°C.

SQL Queries used for analysis

WITH seasonal_data AS (
    SELECT 
        EXTRACT(YEAR FROM starttime) as year,
        CASE 
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (12,1,2) THEN 'Winter'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (3,4,5) THEN 'Spring'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (6,7,8) THEN 'Summer'
            ELSE 'Fall'
        END as season,
        COUNT(*) as trip_count,
        AVG(tripduration_min) as avg_duration,
        AVG(cpw_temperature) as avg_temp
    FROM citi_weather
    GROUP BY 
        EXTRACT(YEAR FROM starttime),
        CASE 
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (12,1,2) THEN 'Winter'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (3,4,5) THEN 'Spring'
            WHEN EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) IN (6,7,8) THEN 'Summer'
            ELSE 'Fall'
        END
)
SELECT * FROM seasonal_data
ORDER BY year, season;
WITH time_periods AS (
    SELECT 
        cpw_temperature,
        usertype,
        CASE 
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 8 THEN 'Morning (8AM)'
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 12 THEN 'Noon'
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 17 THEN 'Afternoon (5PM)'
        END as time_period,
        tripduration_min,
        starttime
    FROM citi_weather
    WHERE EXTRACT(YEAR FROM starttime) = 2019
        AND EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) BETWEEN 5 AND 8  -- Summer months (May to August)
        AND EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) IN (8, 12, 17)
        AND usertype == 'Subscriber'  -- Casual users
        AND tripduration_min > 5 AND tripduration_min < 200  -- Trip duration range
        AND cpw_temperature > 28  -- Temperature above 28°C (81°F)
)
SELECT 
    usertype,
    time_period,
    EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) as month,
    tripduration_min,
    cpw_temperature
FROM time_periods
ORDER BY 
    month,
    time_period;
WITH time_periods AS (
    SELECT 
        cpw_temperature,
        usertype,
        CASE 
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 8 THEN 'Morning (8AM)'
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 12 THEN 'Noon' 
            WHEN EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) = 17 THEN 'Afternoon (5PM)'
        END as time_period,
        starttime
    FROM citi_weather
    WHERE EXTRACT(YEAR FROM starttime) = 2019
        AND EXTRACT(HOUR FROM starttime) IN (8, 12, 17)
        AND tripduration_min > 5 AND tripduration_min < 200  -- Trip duration range
        AND cpw_temperature > 28  -- Temperature above 32°C (89.6°F)
)
SELECT 
    usertype,
    time_period,
    EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime) as month,
    COUNT(*) as number_of_trips,
    cpw_temperature
FROM time_periods
GROUP BY
    usertype,
    time_period,
    EXTRACT(MONTH FROM starttime),
    cpw_temperature
ORDER BY 
    month,
    time_period;

Explanation of above SQL queries

The first query is used to create a table that shows the number of trips taken by users of the bike-sharing service in each season from 2013 to 2019. The table includes the year, season, number of trips, average trip duration, and average temperature for each season. This table is used to create a plot that shows the seasonal patterns in the number of trips taken by users of the bike-sharing service over the years. The second query is used to create a table that shows the trip duration, temperature, and time of day for trips taken by casual users in the summer months of 2019. The table includes the user type, time period, month, trip duration, and temperature for each trip. This table is used to create a spline regression model that analyzes the relationship between temperature, time of day, and trip duration in extreme weather conditions.

Seasonal Pattern visual analysis

# Seasonal Patterns
ggplot(season_type_data, aes(x=year, y=trip_count, fill=season)) +

       x="Year",
       y="Number of Trips") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))

In this plot, we can see that the number of trips taken by users of the bike-sharing service has increased over the years. The number of trips taken in the summer months is higher than in the other seasons. The number of trips taken in the winter months is the lowest. This pattern is consistent across all years from 2013 to 2019. This pattern led me to want to examine the relationship between the temperature and the duration of trips taken by users in different weather conditions. I wanted to focus on the extreme weather conditions, so I decided to analyze the relationship between temperature and trip duration in temperatures above 28°C (81°F). Another decision that was influenced by this graph was to focus on the year 2019 for the regression. As to the fact that this year had the most data points within my collected data set. Also, another finding from this plot is that the number of trips in each year seems to be continuously increasing. Which could be attributed to the fact that the CitiBike service is becoming more popular over the years, and including more stations throughout the 5 boroughs. Lastly, it should be noted that the data for 2016 is missing some entries as seen by the very low number of trips for summertime. However, that error in the data did not effect the overall analysis because the data for 2016 was not used in the regression model.

Model building examining the relationship between temperature and bike trip behavior in hot weather conditions

Model 1 - Number of Trips

# Log transformation of trip duration
numtrips_data$numtrips_log <- log(numtrips_data$number_of_trips)
# Create a spline regression model for temperatures over 32°C
model_t <- lm(numtrips_log ~ cpw_temperature
                                    + 
                                   factor(time_period) + usertype, 
              data = numtrips_data)
modelsummary(model_t,
  title = "Spline Regression Results: Temperature Impact on Number of Trips",

Analysis and Validation of model 1 and 2

Based upon the results from the spline regression with temperatures above 28°C, we can see that the model is statistically significant with a P-Value of near 0. Which means that the model can be used for analysis. However the R-squared value is only .003. Which means that the model explains 0.03% of the variance in trip duration. Another important aspect of this regression is the intercept which has a value of 35.86. This means that without any other factors, the trip duration would be 35.86 minutes. However, once the temperature reaches 32°C, the trip duration decreases by 22.72 minutes for every degree increase in temperature.This is a significant decrease in trip duration and indicates that extreme temperatures have a large impact on trip duration. Furthermore, with an increase of approximately 1.2°C the trip duration will be below zero. Meaning that the trip duration will become negative and thus impossible to occur. Showing how with even a small increase in temperature at the extreme temperature mark that it is has a big effect on trip duration. The slope value for time period is 1.18. This means that the trip duration increases by 1.1 minutes for every change in time period. It changes slightly differently to temperature because the time period variable is a factor. Meaning it has a different relationship with the trip duration. Lastly, this is a small increase in trip duration and indicates that the time of day has a small impact on trip duration.

The AIC and BIC values are 123700 and 123731, respectively. This indicates that the model is not a good fit for the data. The diagnostic plots show that the residuals are not normally distributed and that there is heteroscedasticity in the model. This suggests that the model is not a good fit for the data and that there are other factors that are influencing trip duration in temperatures above 32°C.

Conclusion and Future Work

Perhaps in future analysis, we could include other variables such as humidity, wind speed, and precipitation to see if they have an effect on trip duration in extreme weather conditions. We could also look at other time periods to see if there are any patterns in trip duration during different times of the day. This could help us to better understand the relationship between temperature and trip duration and to identify any factors that may be influencing trip duration in extreme weather conditions. Also, another possibility among unsubscribing customers is that they might be using the service for leisure purposes, and not for commuting. This could be a reason why the trip duration is not affected by the temperature. Also, due to the nature of Manhattan riding a bike on very hot day may be more comfortable than riding the subway or walking. As to the fact that while riding a bike it can generate a much needed breeze on a hot summer day.
